{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641976","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641976"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:34:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:34:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17921"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17921","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17921"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.77,0.14,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10635"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72862"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10635","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10635"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17921"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58332"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5099"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24776"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24779"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72862","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72862"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about type 1 diabetes is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["It is most commonly diagnosed between 18-22 years of age","It is caused by destruction of pancreatic beta cells","It is insulin independent","It is primarily managed with oral hypoglycaemic agents","It is associated with obesity"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt is caused by destruction of pancreatic beta cells\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct statement. Type 1 diabetes is an autoimmune condition where the body\u0027s immune system attacks and destroys the insulin-producing beta cells in the pancreas, leading to insulin deficiency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt is most commonly diagnosed between 18-22 years of age\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Type 1 diabetes is most commonly diagnosed in children and adolescents, although it can occur at any age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt is insulin independent\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Type 1 diabetes is insulin-dependent because the destruction of beta cells results in little to no insulin production, necessitating insulin therapy for management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt is primarily managed with oral hypoglycaemic agents\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Type 1 diabetes is managed with insulin therapy, not oral hypoglycaemic agents, which are used in type 2 diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIt is associated with obesity\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While obesity is a risk factor for type 2 diabetes, type 1 diabetes is not typically associated with obesity and can occur in individuals of any body type.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Type 1 diabetes is an autoimmune condition leading to the destruction of pancreatic beta cells, resulting in insulin deficiency.","Type 1 diabetes is most commonly diagnosed in children and adolescents, but it can occur at any age.","Patients with type 1 diabetes are insulin-dependent due to the lack of endogenous insulin production."],"references":["DiMeglio LA, Evans-Molina C, Oram RA. Type 1 diabetes. Lancet. 2018 Jun 16;391(10138):2449-2462. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(18)31320-5. PMID: 29916386; PMCID: PMC6661119.","Lucier J, Mathias PM. Type 1 Diabetes. 2024 Oct 5. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29939535.","Giwa AM, Ahmed R, Omidian Z, Majety N, Karakus KE, Omer SM, Donner T, Hamad ARA. Current understandings of the pathogenesis of type 1 diabetes: Genetics to environment. World J Diabetes. 2020 Jan 15;11(1):13-25. doi: 10.4239/wjd.v11.i1.13. PMID: 31938470; PMCID: PMC6927819."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58332"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17921"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58332","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58332"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-22T12:39:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-22T12:40:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10635"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72862"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4929","links":{"self":"https://app.eme